g.text: If we do not comply with this rule it might be that clients are unable to catch the derived exceptions (because they don’t expect it). This will cause unhandled exceptions in the system.

g.text: If a return type is less concrete (so more abstract), it might not behave the same as the base class return type. This might cause potential bugs in client code.

g.title: Folded Corner.56
g.desc: When adhering to the Liskov Substitution principle we need le...

g.text: When adhering to the Liskov Substitution principle we need less knowledge of the concrete type, because less variation on be base ‘contract’ is permitted by the concrete type. This results in less conditional checks and reduces the overall complexity of the system.

g.title: Folded Corner.85
g.desc: Clients of a collection of base class items expect that each ...

g.text: Clients of a collection of base class items expect that each item behaves according to the ‘contract’ of the base class. Using the collection of base class items according this contract might cause a failure when the LSP is not adhered to. 1) In case the programmer is using this collection he is forced to immerse into the concrete implementation when an error occurs.2) A bug might be introduced in case the programmer adds a new item to this collection and violates LSP. The new item, in case of a ‘large’ system , is being ‘swallowed’ and we cannot oversee where and how it is being used.

g.title: Folded Corner.89
g.desc: We often use inheritance to adhere to open-closed principle, ...

g.text: We often use inheritance to adhere to open-closed principle, because inheritance makes it possible to added new functionality while minimizing the adjustment of existing code. Adding new functionality, using inheritance, can only be done is a ‘safe’ and ‘reliable’ way when we adhere to LSP.
